What is “Making It” as an actor?
•
Honestly it’s different for every single person. I read people on r/acting Reddit ask about wanting to “Make It” and most people are referring to becoming “famous” or “landing a life changing role”.
•
If you are constantly waiting for that ONE moment to make it, a majority of the time you will be unhappy. Since I haven’t landed a Marvel role, am I a failure? In my eyes no. I’ve had 200ish auditions over the past couple years and landed an amount I can count on one hand. Am I failure because I didn’t book 98 percent of the time? No.
•
In the past, making it was getting into my BFA program in Edmonton, Alberta. It was simply getting my first audition. It was graduating. It was getting a callback. It was landing my first ever role. Etc.
•
Have large goals. Absolutely do that. (Cough still want that Marvel role). But enjoy every other tiny little small thing you achieve on the way. Steps to Success right Giannis.

4 SETS OF 12.
•
You see this everywhere. Hint hint. It doesn’t actually just mean 12. It means hit around 12. 12 reps is an awesome marker for building muscle sooo hitting around it is perfect. The point here is to go til failure or NEAR failure. If you fail at 8 reps, that’s okay, next time maybe you can get 9. But if you’re pumping around 16 and it’s too easy, find a weight that puts your around that 12 mark.

If you’re wanting to start working out but you don’t know where to start START SMALL.
•
Start with something you figure you can do once a week (or something SUPER FOR SURE manageable) and then build from there.

Happy Chest Day:

Flat Bench Press
5-6 sets X 6-12 reps

Incline DB Flies
3-4 Sets of 15-30 reps

#chestday #chest #workout #bodybuilding #actor

These are some of my most (if not my MOST) used Chest Exercises. I try not to swap out exercises too much so I can see some real progress and have better gains with consistency
•
Flat Bench Press
-THE chest exercise. You can go heavier here than a lot of other exercises and hit the biggest part of your chest.
•
Incline Bench Press
-targets upper chest. Hitting this more often as it’s a pretty weak movement for me. Try not to make it such a high angle that your anterior delts (front of your shoulders) is getting too much action. Chest first. Shoulders will jump in inevitably.
•
Incline Single Arm Cable Flies
-targets upper chest. single arm because I can get MORE flexion than just a bar or even dual dumbbells. Single arm because I can compensate with one arm if the other is weaker, so this helps me balance the strength/size gains.
•
Decline Cable Flies
-targets main part of your chest. mostly a finisher for me. Not much of an advantage over doing  Bench press but a bit more flexion. (Different story if you do single arm). Feel good exercise so I like to finish with it.

Use RIR (Reps in Reserve) to make sure you’re hitting the proper stimulus for Muscle Growth. Sitting within a certain rep range (10 reps) may work for some people, but once you become more aware of your effort in your workouts, pushing yourself closer to failure for muscle building is key. 🔑 
•
For example:
Incline Bench Press (4 Sets of 10 reps). If you can do 2-3 more reps before failure, do so (safely).

PR DEADLIFT BABY

Today was a complete surprise for me. I haven’t been deadlifting heavy AT ALL for the past six months or so. I’ve mainly been working on my Bench Press (as most people who follow my page know). So when @lucyybuhat had deadlifts programmed and I had a “rest day” from my upper body, I thought I’d play around….and 415 HAPPENED. 10lbs up from my last PR.

Now I’m trying to assess WHY/HOW this result came to be and I’ve come to three possible ideas.

1) The build up sets to my top set came from something @jessebifano taught me at the Strength camp that was held at @trainwestvan . Sometimes when I build up to a heavy top set I just go by feel and that can tend to lead to more energy wasted. So my sets were 135lbs - 225lbs - 295lbs - 355lbs - 395lbs -  415lbs. In the last that seems like CRAZY jumps. But my rule was to never jump up higher than my last jump. So +90lbs | +70lbs | +45lbs | +25lbs. Less energy spent = able to lift heavier?

2) Mostly Accessory + No Heavy Deadz. Like I said I’ve mostly been benching the last half year but I’ve made a point to make sure I’m getting my “leg days” in. And that’s mostly High Rep isolated movements like RDLS. I couldn’t even think of more excesses that I’ve been doing more than deficit RDLS so I’ll end it there.

3) Random Feeling Good Day. Some days are just randomly good and any person who works out will tell you those days where you feel amazing can just come out of anywhere.
